    "summary": "One objection to constitutive nature, but could accept it",
    "content": "**My specific objection:** \"Constitutive nature\" is philosophically precise but has a running-text weight problem. In the 道德仁义礼 passage, 德 appears repeatedly and in compounds. \"All things have their constitutive nature\" works once. \"The constitutive nature generates humaneness, humaneness generates rightness\" starts to feel labored. \"Defining character\" is two syllables shorter and reads faster in the sustained, rapid-fire sequence of that passage.\n\n**However:** If the team prefers \"constitutive nature\" for its philosophical precision, I can accept it. The Kantian resonance (constitutive vs. regulative) is genuinely useful -- it signals to philosophically literate readers that 德 is a *principle that actively structures experience*, not a passive property. That is a real advantage over \"defining character,\" which is more neutral.\n\n**My position:** I slightly prefer \"defining character\" for readability but acknowledge \"constitutive nature\" is more precise. I would not object to either. If forced to choose between them as the only two options, I would defer to whichever the translator finds easier to work with in the actual prose.\n"
  }
